Taiwan Stocks: Elpida Memory, Sintek Photronic, Technics Oil

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-02-25T05:58:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-25/china-steel-elpida-hon-hai-precision-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  Taiwan  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and prices are as of the 1:30 p.m. in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 58.01, or 0.7 percent, to 8,599.65.
The benchmark fell 2.8 percent this week and 6 percent this
month. Taiwan stock market will be closed on Feb. 28 for a
public holiday.    Elpida Memory Inc . (916665 TT), the world’s third-largest
maker of computer-memory chips, gained 1.9 percent to NT$21.70
on its first day of trading on the Taiwan Stock Exchange. The
Tokyo-based chipmaker sold shares for NT$21.30 each, according
to a statement to the Tokyo Stock Exchange. The company’s Chief
Executive Officer Yukio Sakamoto said it scrapped plans to merge
with Taiwanese chipmakers after opposition from the target
companies.    HTC Corp . (2498 TT) surged by the 6.8 percent daily limit
to a record NT$1065 on speculation the sale of new handsets from
next month will boost revenue, said Chen Wei-hang, an analyst at
President Capital Management Corp. HTC Chief Financial Officer
Winston Yung didn’t answer two calls to his office at Taoyuan,
Taiwan.    Sintek Photronic Corp . (3049 TT) increased 6.6 percent to
NT$29.05, the highest level since May 2004. The color-filter
maker’s board decided to seek a five-year loan of as much as
NT$7.2 billion ($242 million), the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based company
said in a statement to the stock exchange yesterday.    Technics Oil & Gas Ltd . (911613 TT) rose 6.8 percent to
NT$12.50. The Singapore-based provider of engineering services
to the oil and gas industry made its debut in Taiwan. The
company has said it will raise S$13.2 million ($10.4 million)
selling Taiwan Depositary Receipts priced at NT$11.70 each.    Walsin Lihwa Corp . (1605 TT) increased 3.6 percent to
NT$15.75. The electric wire and cable maker bought NT$550
million of Powertec Energy Corp. shares, or a 14.1 percent
stake, the Taipei-based company said in a statement to the stock
exchange yesterday.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 